    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-17T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-17T23:00:00-05:00" n="426"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d426">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13782: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-18T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 18, 1936—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received December 18—8:45
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>360. I have just seen Dr. Kung and have conveyed to him our Government’s concern
                    over safety of General Chiang. Dr. Kung asked me to express to the President and
                    to you his thanks. Dr. Kung expressed himself as hopeful of a solution which
                    would result in the safety of General Chiang although he admitted that the
                    situation was still very serious. He told me that he expected General Chiang
                    Ting Wen in Nanking this morning.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department; code text mailed to Tokyo and Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
